<_X_book code="LAM">





<!-- ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ -->
<_X_chapter sid="LAM 1">
<verse sid="LAM 1:1"/>And it happened, after Israel was taken captive and Ierousalem was laid waste, Ieremias sat weeping and gave this lament over Ierousalem and said: <note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:1</char><char closed="false" style="ft">alpha</char></note>How the city sat alone, she who was full of peoples! She has become like a widow-- multiplied among the nations! A ruler among the countries, she has become tribute.<verse eid="LAM 1:1"/>

<verse sid="LAM 1:2"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:2</char><char closed="false" style="ft">beth</char></note>Weeping she wept in the night, and her tears were on her cheeks; of all those who love her there is no one to comfort her. All that were her friends dealt treacherously with her; they became enemies to her.<verse eid="LAM 1:2"/>

<verse sid="LAM 1:3"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:3</char><char closed="false" style="ft">gimel</char></note>Judea was deported from<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:3</char><char closed="false" style="ft">Possibly 'because of'</char></note> her humiliation and from<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:3</char><char closed="false" style="ft">Possibly 'because of'</char></note> greatness of her slavery; she sat among nations; she has found no rest; all those pursuing her have overtaken her among her oppressors.<verse eid="LAM 1:3"/>

<verse sid="LAM 1:4"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:4</char><char closed="false" style="ft">daleth</char></note>Roads to Sion mourn because there is none that comes to a feast; all her gates are obliterated; her priests groan; her young girls are being led away, and she, being embittered in herself.<verse eid="LAM 1:4"/>

<verse sid="LAM 1:5"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:5</char><char closed="false" style="ft">he</char></note>Those that oppress her have become head, and her enemies kept flourishing, because the Lord humbled her for the multitude of her impieties; her babes went away in captivity before an oppressor.<verse eid="LAM 1:5"/>

<verse sid="LAM 1:6"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:6</char><char closed="false" style="ft">ouau</char></note>And from daughter Sion has departed<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:6</char><char closed="false" style="ft">'has departed':  Ziegler = 'was removed'</char></note> all her majesty. Her rulers became like rams that find no pasture, and they were going in no strength before a pursuer.<verse eid="LAM 1:6"/>

<verse sid="LAM 1:7"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:7</char><char closed="false" style="ft">zai</char></note>Ierousalem remembered days of her humiliation and her rebuffs. As for all her desired objects that were from days of old-- when her people fell into the hands of an oppressor, then there was no one to help her. When her enemies saw, they laughed at her being settled.<verse eid="LAM 1:7"/>

<verse sid="LAM 1:8"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:8</char><char closed="false" style="ft">heth</char></note>Ierousalem sinned sin, so she became ashaken; all those that honored her humiliated her, for they saw her shame; indeed, while she herself is groaning, she also turned her face away.<verse eid="LAM 1:8"/>

<verse sid="LAM 1:9"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:9</char><char closed="false" style="ft">teth</char></note>Her uncleanness was from<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:9</char><char closed="false" style="ft">'was from':  Possibly 'began with'</char></note> her feet; she did not remember her extremities. And she brought down things of great size; there is no one to comfort her. "O Lord, look at my humiliation, for an enemy became great!"<verse eid="LAM 1:9"/>

<verse sid="LAM 1:10"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:10</char><char closed="false" style="ft">ioth</char></note>An oppressor spread out his hand over all her desired objects; for she saw nations enter into her holy precinct, with reference to whom you commanded that they not enter into your assembly.<verse eid="LAM 1:10"/>

<verse sid="LAM 1:11"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:11</char><char closed="false" style="ft">chaph</char></note>All her people are groaning as they search for bread; they gave her desired objects for food to restore life. Look, O Lord, and see that I have become one dishonored.<verse eid="LAM 1:11"/>

<verse sid="LAM 1:12"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:12</char><char closed="false" style="ft">labd</char></note>It is nothing to you, all you who pass along the road! Turn, and see if there is a sorrow like my sorrow, which has happened; the Lord humbled me on the day of the wrath of his anger.<verse eid="LAM 1:12"/>

<verse sid="LAM 1:13"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:13</char><char closed="false" style="ft">mem</char></note>From his height he sent fire in my bones; he brought it down; he spread a net for my feet; he turned me backwards; he gave me as one<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:13</char><char closed="false" style="ft">I.e. 'a female'</char></note> put away, suffering pain all day long.<verse eid="LAM 1:13"/>

<verse sid="LAM 1:14"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:14</char><char closed="false" style="ft">noun</char></note>He was kept awake over all my impious deeds; by my hands they were plaited together; they came up upon my neck; my strength became weak; because the Lord gave them in my hands, I shall not be able to stand.<verse eid="LAM 1:14"/>

<verse sid="LAM 1:15"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:15</char><char closed="false" style="ft">samch</char></note>The Lord removed all my strong men from my midst; he proclaimed a season against me to crush my choice men; the Lord trod the wine vat for virgin daughter Iouda. (16) For these things I weep.<verse eid="LAM 1:15"/>

<verse sid="LAM 1:16"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:16</char><char closed="false" style="ft">ain</char></note>My eye has brought down water, because the one to comfort me is far from me, the one to restore my life; my sons became put away, for an enemy prevailed.<verse eid="LAM 1:16"/>

<verse sid="LAM 1:17"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:17</char><char closed="false" style="ft">pe</char></note>Sion spread out her hands; there is no one to comfort her; the Lord commanded regarding Iakob; around him are those oppressing him. Ierousalem became as one<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:17</char><char closed="false" style="ft">I.e. 'a female'</char></note> sitting apart<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:17</char><char closed="false" style="ft">'sitting apart':  I.e. 'in menstruation'</char></note> among them.<verse eid="LAM 1:17"/>

<verse sid="LAM 1:18"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:18</char><char closed="false" style="ft">sade</char></note>The Lord is in the right, because I have made his mouth bitter. Hear then, all you peoples, and behold my sorrow; my young women and my young men went away in captivity.<verse eid="LAM 1:18"/>

<verse sid="LAM 1:19"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:19</char><char closed="false" style="ft">koph</char></note>I called to my lovers, but they deceived me; my priests and my elders failed in the city, because they sought food for themselves to restore their life, and they did not find it.<verse eid="LAM 1:19"/>

<verse sid="LAM 1:20"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:20</char><char closed="false" style="ft">res</char></note>See, O Lord, that I am distressed; my stomach churned; my heart was turned in me, because I have embittered, when embittering. Outside a dagger made childless, just as death at home.<verse eid="LAM 1:20"/>

<verse sid="LAM 1:21"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:21</char><char closed="false" style="ft">sen</char></note>Hear then, because I am groaning; there is no one to comfort me. All my enemies heard of my troubles, and they rejoiced that you have acted. You brought on the day; you proclaimed the time, and they became just like me.<verse eid="LAM 1:21"/>

<verse sid="LAM 1:22"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">1:22</char><char closed="false" style="ft">thau</char></note>May all their evil doing come before you, and glean every grape of theirs as you gleaned in connection with all my sins, for my groanings are many and my heart is grieved.<verse eid="LAM 1:22"/>
</_X_chapter>




<!-- ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ -->
<_X_chapter sid="LAM 2">
<verse sid="LAM 2:1"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">2:1</char><char closed="false" style="ft">alpha</char></note>How the Lord brought gloom in his anger over daughter Sion! He has thrown down from heaven to earth the splendor of Israel. And he did not remember the footstool of his feet<verse eid="LAM 2:1"/>

<verse sid="LAM 2:2"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">2:2</char><char closed="false" style="ft">beth</char></note>in the day of his anger. (2) The Lord has drowned without sparing all the beauties of Iakob; in his wrath he broke down the strongholds of daughter Iouda; he glued them<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">2:2</char><char closed="false" style="ft">Lacking in Greek</char></note> to the ground; he profaned her king and her rulers.<verse eid="LAM 2:2"/>

<verse sid="LAM 2:3"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">2:3</char><char closed="false" style="ft">gimel</char></note>He broke off in the anger of his wrath every horn of Israel; he turned back his right hand from before the enemy, and he kindled in Iakob a flame like fire, and it consumed all things around.<verse eid="LAM 2:3"/>

<verse sid="LAM 2:4"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">2:4</char><char closed="false" style="ft">daleth</char></note>He bent his bow as an enemy; he fixed firm his right hand as an opponent, and he killed all that my eyes desired in the tent of daughter Sion; he poured out his wrath like fire.<verse eid="LAM 2:4"/>

<verse sid="LAM 2:5"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">2:5</char><char closed="false" style="ft">he</char></note>The Lord became like an enemy; he drowned Israel; he drowned her bastions; he laid in ruins its strongholds, and he multiplied in daughter Iouda a woman humiliated and humbled.<verse eid="LAM 2:5"/>

<verse sid="LAM 2:6"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">2:6</char><char closed="false" style="ft">ouau</char></note>And he tore down his covert like a vine; he ruined his feast; the Lord made feast and sabbath to be forgotten in Sion, and he provoked in the indignation of his anger king and priest and ruler.<verse eid="LAM 2:6"/>

<verse sid="LAM 2:7"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">2:7</char><char closed="false" style="ft">zai</char></note>The Lord rejected his altar; he shook off his holy precinct; he crushed by the hand of an enemy the wall of her bastions; they gave forth a cry in the house of the Lord as on a feast day.<verse eid="LAM 2:7"/>

<verse sid="LAM 2:8"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">2:8</char><char closed="false" style="ft">heth</char></note>And the Lord returned to lay in ruins the wall of daughter Sion; he stretched out a measuring line; he did not turn back his hand from drowning, and the outer wall mourned, and the wall became weak along with it.<verse eid="LAM 2:8"/>

<verse sid="LAM 2:9"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">2:9</char><char closed="false" style="ft">teth</char></note>Her gates were stuck in the ground; he destroyed and shattered her bars, her king and her rulers among the nations. There is no law; indeed, her prophets did not see a vision from the Lord.<verse eid="LAM 2:9"/>

<verse sid="LAM 2:10"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">2:10</char><char closed="false" style="ft">ioth</char></note>They sat on the ground; elders of daughter Sion were silent; they brought up dust on their head; they girded themselves with sackcloth; they brought down to the ground leading young women of Ierousalem.<verse eid="LAM 2:10"/>

<verse sid="LAM 2:11"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">2:11</char><char closed="false" style="ft">chaph</char></note>My eyes failed in tears; my stomach churned; my honor was poured out on the ground because of the fracture of the daughter of my people, as infant and suckling fail in city squares.<verse eid="LAM 2:11"/>

<verse sid="LAM 2:12"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">2:12</char><char closed="false" style="ft">labd</char></note>To their mothers they said, "Where is bread and wine?" as they faint like the wounded in city squares, as their life is poured out into their mothers' bosom.<verse eid="LAM 2:12"/>

<verse sid="LAM 2:13"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">2:13</char><char closed="false" style="ft">mem</char></note>What witness shall I bear of you, or to what shall I compare you, O daughter Ierousalem? With what shall I equate you and comfort you, O virgin daughter Sion? For the cup of your ruin was made great; who will heal you?<verse eid="LAM 2:13"/>

<verse sid="LAM 2:14"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">2:14</char><char closed="false" style="ft">noun</char></note>Your prophets saw for you what is worthless and foolishness, and they did not expose your injustice, to turn your captivity around; and they saw for you worthless messages-- and banishments!<verse eid="LAM 2:14"/>

<verse sid="LAM 2:15"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">2:15</char><char closed="false" style="ft">samch</char></note>All who pass along the road clapped their hands at you; they hissed and wagged their head at daughter Ierousalem: "Is this the city, of which they say, 'Crown of splendor, Joy of all the earth?'"<verse eid="LAM 2:15"/>

<verse sid="LAM 2:16"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">2:16</char><char closed="false" style="ft">ain</char></note>All your enemies opened their mouth against you; they hissed and gnashed their teeth; they cried, "We have swallowed her! Only, this is the day that we were expecting; we have found it; we have seen!"<verse eid="LAM 2:16"/>

<verse sid="LAM 2:17"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">2:17</char><char closed="false" style="ft">pe</char></note>The Lord has done what he purposed; he has carried out his words, what he commanded from ancient days; he demolished and did not spare, and he has made the enemy rejoice over you; he exalted the horn of the one oppressing you.<verse eid="LAM 2:17"/>

<verse sid="LAM 2:18"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">2:18</char><char closed="false" style="ft">sade</char></note>Their heart cried out to the Lord: O walls of Sion! Bring down tears like wadis day and night! Give yourself no calming down! May your eye not be silent, O daughter!<verse eid="LAM 2:18"/>

<verse sid="LAM 2:19"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">2:19</char><char closed="false" style="ft">koph</char></note>Arise, give a cry of joy in the night at the beginnings of your watch! Pour out like water your heart before the presence of the Lord! Lift your hands to him for the life of your babes who faint with hunger at the beginning of all exits.<verse eid="LAM 2:19"/>

<verse sid="LAM 2:20"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">2:20</char><char closed="false" style="ft">res</char></note>Look, Lord, and consider for whom have you gleaned grapes thus. Will women eat the fruit of their womb? A butcher<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">2:20</char><char closed="false" style="ft">Or 'cook'</char></note> made a gleaning. Will you kill in the holy precinct of the Lord priest and prophet?<verse eid="LAM 2:20"/>

<verse sid="LAM 2:21"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">2:21</char><char closed="false" style="ft">sen</char></note>Young child and old man fell asleep on the ground in the exits; my young women and my young men fell by the sword; in the day of your anger you killed; you slaughtered them; you did not spare.<verse eid="LAM 2:21"/>

<verse sid="LAM 2:22"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">2:22</char><char closed="false" style="ft">thau</char></note>He invited my sojournings from all around as to a feast day, and on the day of the anger of the Lord there was no one saved and left behind, as I<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">2:22</char><char closed="false" style="ft">Possibly 'the Lord'</char></note> prevailed and multiplied all my enemies.<verse eid="LAM 2:22"/>
</_X_chapter>




<!-- ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ -->
<_X_chapter sid="LAM 3">
<verse sid="LAM 3:1"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:1</char><char closed="false" style="ft">alpha</char></note>I am the man who sees poverty by the rod of his wrath;<verse eid="LAM 3:1"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:2"/>he took me along and led me away into darkness and not light;<verse eid="LAM 3:2"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:3"/>only, against me he turned his hand all day long.<verse eid="LAM 3:3"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:4"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:4</char><char closed="false" style="ft">beth</char></note>He made my flesh and my skin old; he shattered my bones;<verse eid="LAM 3:4"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:5"/>he built<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:5</char><char closed="false" style="ft">Or 'walled'</char></note> up against me and encircled my head, and it became exhausted;<verse eid="LAM 3:5"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:6"/>he made me sit in dark places like the dead of long ago.<verse eid="LAM 3:6"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:7"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:7</char><char closed="false" style="ft">gimel</char></note>He built<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:7</char><char closed="false" style="ft">Or 'walled'</char></note> up against me, and I shall not go out; he made my brass heavy;<verse eid="LAM 3:7"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:8"/>indeed, because I shall cry out and shout for help, he shut out my prayer;<verse eid="LAM 3:8"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:9"/>he built<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:9</char><char closed="false" style="ft">Or 'walled'</char></note> up my ways; he fenced in my paths; he troubled me.<verse eid="LAM 3:9"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:10"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:10</char><char closed="false" style="ft">daleth</char></note>He is to me a she-bear lying in wait, a lion in hiding;<verse eid="LAM 3:10"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:11"/>he pursued a runaway and pulled me down; he made me one<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:11</char><char closed="false" style="ft">I.e. 'a female'</char></note> put away;<verse eid="LAM 3:11"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:12"/>he bent his bow and set me up as a target for an arrow.<verse eid="LAM 3:12"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:13"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:13</char><char closed="false" style="ft">he</char></note>He made sons of his quiver enter in my kidneys;<verse eid="LAM 3:13"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:14"/>I became a laughingstock to all my people, their strumming<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:14</char><char closed="false" style="ft">Possibly 'psalm'</char></note> all day long;<verse eid="LAM 3:14"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:15"/>he has fed me with bitterness; he has made me drunk with gall.<verse eid="LAM 3:15"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:16"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:16</char><char closed="false" style="ft">ouau</char></note>And he broke out my teeth with a pebble; he fed me tidbits of ashes.<verse eid="LAM 3:16"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:17"/>And he thrust my soul away from peace; I forgot good things.<verse eid="LAM 3:17"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:18"/>And I said, "My victory perished, and my hope from the Lord."<verse eid="LAM 3:18"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:19"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:19</char><char closed="false" style="ft">zai</char></note>I remembered from my poverty and out of my persecution;<verse eid="LAM 3:19"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:20"/>bitterness and gall (20) my soul will remember and will talk idly at<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:20</char><char closed="false" style="ft">'talk idly at':  Perhaps 'complain to'</char></note> me;<verse eid="LAM 3:20"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:21"/>I will place it in my heart; therefore I will wait.<verse eid="LAM 3:21"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:22"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:22</char><char closed="false" style="ft">heth</char></note>The mercies of the Lord are that we have not expired, that his compassion has not come to an end.<verse eid="LAM 3:22"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:23"/>They are new in the early mornings; great is your faithfulness.<verse eid="LAM 3:23"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:24"/>"The Lord is my portion," said my soul, "therefore I will wait for him."<verse eid="LAM 3:24"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:25"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:25</char><char closed="false" style="ft">teth</char></note>The Lord is good to those who wait for him, to the soul that will seek him.<verse eid="LAM 3:25"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:26"/>A good thing it is-- and it<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:26</char><char closed="false" style="ft">I.e. 'my soul'</char></note> will wait and be quiet for the salvation of the Lord.<verse eid="LAM 3:26"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:27"/>It is a good thing for a man when he bears a yoke in his youth.<verse eid="LAM 3:27"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:28"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:28</char><char closed="false" style="ft">ioth</char></note>He will sit alone and be silent, because he raised it on himself;<verse eid="LAM 3:28"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:29"/>he will give his mouth in a heap of earth, if perhaps there is hope;<verse eid="LAM 3:29"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:30"/>he will give a cheek to him that smites it; he will be fed with insults.<verse eid="LAM 3:30"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:31"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:31</char><char closed="false" style="ft">chaph</char></note>For the Lord will not reject forever;<verse eid="LAM 3:31"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:32"/>for he who humbled will have compassion, according to the abundance of his mercy;<verse eid="LAM 3:32"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:33"/>for he did not answer from his heart, and he abased a man's sons:<verse eid="LAM 3:33"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:34"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:34</char><char closed="false" style="ft">labd</char></note>to abase under his feet all the prisoners of the land,<verse eid="LAM 3:34"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:35"/>to turn aside a man's case in the presence of the Most High,<verse eid="LAM 3:35"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:36"/>to condemn a person when he goes to law-- did not the Lord see?<verse eid="LAM 3:36"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:37"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:37</char><char closed="false" style="ft">mem</char></note>Who is this that spoke, and it happened? Did the Lord not command it?<verse eid="LAM 3:37"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:38"/>Will bad and good not come from the mouth of the Most High?<verse eid="LAM 3:38"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:39"/>Why will any person alive grumble, a man, concerning his sin?<verse eid="LAM 3:39"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:40"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:40</char><char closed="false" style="ft">noun</char></note>Our way was investigated and examined, and so let us return to the Lord.<verse eid="LAM 3:40"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:41"/>Let us take up our hearts in our hands to a high one in heaven.<verse eid="LAM 3:41"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:42"/>We<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:42</char><char closed="false" style="ft">preceded by Ziegler = 'we sinned'</char></note> have acted impiously, and we embittered you<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:42</char><char closed="false" style="ft">Lacking in Greek</char></note>, and you were not appeased.<verse eid="LAM 3:42"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:43"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:43</char><char closed="false" style="ft">samch</char></note>You covered us over in wrath and pursued us; you killed; you did not spare.<verse eid="LAM 3:43"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:44"/>You covered yourself with a cloud on account of prayer;<verse eid="LAM 3:44"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:45"/>you set us in the midst of the peoples to make me stoop and be rejected.<verse eid="LAM 3:45"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:46"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:46</char><char closed="false" style="ft">pe</char></note>All our enemies opened their mouth against us.<verse eid="LAM 3:46"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:47"/>Fear and a pit have come upon us, lifting up and destruction.<verse eid="LAM 3:47"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:48"/>My eye will bring down emissions of water for the fracture of the daughter of my people.<verse eid="LAM 3:48"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:49"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:49</char><char closed="false" style="ft">ain</char></note>My eye was exhausted, and I will not be silent so that there will be no calming down<verse eid="LAM 3:49"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:50"/>until the Lord stoops down and looks from heaven.<verse eid="LAM 3:50"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:51"/>My eye will glean<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:51</char><char closed="false" style="ft">Perhaps 'strip bare'</char></note> my soul more than all daughters of the city.<verse eid="LAM 3:51"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:52"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:52</char><char closed="false" style="ft">sade</char></note>Hunting my enemies hunted me like a sparrow, without cause;<verse eid="LAM 3:52"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:53"/>they condemned my life to death in a cistern and placed a stone over me;<verse eid="LAM 3:53"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:54"/>water flowed over my head; I said, "I am rejected."<verse eid="LAM 3:54"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:55"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:55</char><char closed="false" style="ft">koph</char></note>I called on your name, O Lord, from the lowest cistern;<verse eid="LAM 3:55"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:56"/>you heard my voice: "Do not cover your ears to my plea!"<verse eid="LAM 3:56"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:57"/>You came near to help me in the day when I called on you; you said to me, "Do not fear!"<verse eid="LAM 3:57"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:58"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:58</char><char closed="false" style="ft">res</char></note>You adjudicated the causes of my soul, O Lord; you have redeemed my life.<verse eid="LAM 3:58"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:59"/>You saw my troubles, O Lord; you judged my case.<verse eid="LAM 3:59"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:60"/>You saw all their revenge, all their schemes against me.<verse eid="LAM 3:60"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:61"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:61</char><char closed="false" style="ft">sen</char></note>You have heard their insults, all their schemes against me,<verse eid="LAM 3:61"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:62"/>lips of my opponents and their machinations against me all day long.<verse eid="LAM 3:62"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:63"/>Consider their sitting and their rising: I am their strumming<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:63</char><char closed="false" style="ft">Possibly 'psalm'</char></note>.<verse eid="LAM 3:63"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:64"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">3:64</char><char closed="false" style="ft">thau</char></note>You shall render a repayment to them, O Lord, according to the works of their hands;<verse eid="LAM 3:64"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:65"/>you shall repay to them a shielding of heart, your hardship for them.<verse eid="LAM 3:65"/>

<verse sid="LAM 3:66"/>You shall pursue in anger and exterminate them beneath the sky, O Lord.<verse eid="LAM 3:66"/>
</_X_chapter>




<!-- ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ -->
<_X_chapter sid="LAM 4">
<verse sid="LAM 4:1"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:1</char><char closed="false" style="ft">alpha</char></note>How gold will grow dim; the good silver will be altered! Consecrated stones were poured out at the beginning of all exits.<verse eid="LAM 4:1"/>

<verse sid="LAM 4:2"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:2</char><char closed="false" style="ft">beth</char></note>The precious sons of Sion who were lifted up with gold-- how they were reckoned as earthen pots, works of a potter's hands.<verse eid="LAM 4:2"/>

<verse sid="LAM 4:3"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:3</char><char closed="false" style="ft">gimel</char></note>Indeed, dragons bared their breasts; their whelps sucked; the daughters of my people are incorrigible, like an ostrich in the wilderness.<verse eid="LAM 4:3"/>

<verse sid="LAM 4:4"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:4</char><char closed="false" style="ft">daleth</char></note>The tongue of the suckling stuck to its throat with thirst; babes begged for food; there was no one to break it up for them.<verse eid="LAM 4:4"/>

<verse sid="LAM 4:5"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:5</char><char closed="false" style="ft">he</char></note>Those who eat delicacies were put away in the exits; those nursed in scarlet wrapped themselves in dung.<verse eid="LAM 4:5"/>

<verse sid="LAM 4:6"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:6</char><char closed="false" style="ft">ouau</char></note>And the lawlessness of the daughter of my people was great, beyond the lawlessness of Sodoma, which was overthrown, as it were, with haste, and they did not labor their hands with her.<verse eid="LAM 4:6"/>

<verse sid="LAM 4:7"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:7</char><char closed="false" style="ft">zai</char></note>Her Nazirites were pronounced<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:7</char><char closed="false" style="ft">Or 'made'</char></note> purer than snow; they shone brighter than milk; they were made redder than stones; their branch<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:7</char><char closed="false" style="ft">Or 'fragment'</char></note> was of lapis lazuli.<verse eid="LAM 4:7"/>

<verse sid="LAM 4:8"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:8</char><char closed="false" style="ft">heth</char></note>Their appearance was darker than soot; they were not recognized in the exits; their skin had stiffened on their bones; they were withered; they became like wood.<verse eid="LAM 4:8"/>

<verse sid="LAM 4:9"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:9</char><char closed="false" style="ft">teth</char></note>The wounded from the sword were more noble than the wounded from hunger; they walked, stabbed<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:9</char><char closed="false" style="ft">I.e. 'by hunger'</char></note>, apart from<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:9</char><char closed="false" style="ft">'apart from':  I.e. 'without'</char></note> the produce of the fields.<verse eid="LAM 4:9"/>

<verse sid="LAM 4:10"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:10</char><char closed="false" style="ft">ioth</char></note>Hands of compassionate women boiled their children; they became their food in the fracture of the daughter of my people.<verse eid="LAM 4:10"/>

<verse sid="LAM 4:11"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:11</char><char closed="false" style="ft">chaph</char></note>The Lord completed his wrath; he poured out the anger of his wrath and kindled a fire in Sion, and it consumed her foundations.<verse eid="LAM 4:11"/>

<verse sid="LAM 4:12"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:12</char><char closed="false" style="ft">labd</char></note>The kings of the earth did not believe, none of the inhabitants of the world, that enemy and oppressor would enter through the gates of Ierousalem.<verse eid="LAM 4:12"/>

<verse sid="LAM 4:13"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:13</char><char closed="false" style="ft">mem</char></note>It was due to the sins of her prophets, the injustices of her priests, those who shed the blood of the righteous in the midst of her.<verse eid="LAM 4:13"/>

<verse sid="LAM 4:14"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:14</char><char closed="false" style="ft">noun</char></note>Her watchers were shaken in the exits; they were defiled with blood. Since they could not help it, they touch their garments.<verse eid="LAM 4:14"/>

<verse sid="LAM 4:15"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:15</char><char closed="false" style="ft">samch</char></note>Away from the unclean! Call them! Away! Away! Do not touch! For they were set ablaze; indeed they were shaken. Say among the nations, "They will by no means add to live as resident aliens."<verse eid="LAM 4:15"/>

<verse sid="LAM 4:16"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:16</char><char closed="false" style="ft">ain</char></note>The presence of the Lord is their portion; he will not add to look upon them; they did not receive the person of the priests; they granted no mercy to the elders.<verse eid="LAM 4:16"/>

<verse sid="LAM 4:17"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:17</char><char closed="false" style="ft">pe</char></note>While we were still alive, our eyes failed; our eyes failed regarding help for us, vainly; while we were looking steadily,<verse eid="LAM 4:17"/>

<verse sid="LAM 4:18"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:18</char><char closed="false" style="ft">sade</char></note>we looked steadily to a nation that does not save. (18) We hunted our small ones<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:18</char><char closed="false" style="ft">'small ones':  I.e. 'children'</char></note> so that they might not walk in our squares.<verse eid="LAM 4:18"/>

<verse sid="LAM 4:19"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:19</char><char closed="false" style="ft">koph</char></note>Our time has drawn near; our days have been fulfilled; our time is at hand. (19) Our pursuers were swifter than eagles in the sky; they clung to us<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:19</char><char closed="false" style="ft">Lacking in Greek</char></note> on the mountains; they lay in wait for us in the wilderness.<verse eid="LAM 4:19"/>

<verse sid="LAM 4:20"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:20</char><char closed="false" style="ft">res</char></note>The Lord's anointed, the breath of our face, was captured by their destructions<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:20</char><char closed="false" style="ft">Possibly 'corruptions'</char></note>-- of whom we said, "In his shade we shall live among the nations."<verse eid="LAM 4:20"/>

<verse sid="LAM 4:21"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:21</char><char closed="false" style="ft">sen</char></note>Rejoice, and be glad, O daughter Idumea, you who live in the land; indeed, the cup of the Lord will pass to you; you will become drunk and spill.<verse eid="LAM 4:21"/>

<verse sid="LAM 4:22"/><note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">4:22</char><char closed="false" style="ft">thau</char></note>Your lawlessness is ended, O Daughter Sion; he will not add to exile you; he visited your lawlessness, O Daughter Edom; he uncovered your impious deeds.<verse eid="LAM 4:22"/>
</_X_chapter>




<!-- ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ -->
<_X_chapter sid="LAM 5">
<verse sid="LAM 5:1"/>Remember, O Lord, what has befallen us. Look, and see our disgrace!<verse eid="LAM 5:1"/>

<verse sid="LAM 5:2"/>Our inheritance has been turned over to foreigners, our homes to strangers.<verse eid="LAM 5:2"/>

<verse sid="LAM 5:3"/>We have become orphans; there is no father; our mothers are like widows.<verse eid="LAM 5:3"/>

<verse sid="LAM 5:4"/>Since our days, our wood came by exchange.<verse eid="LAM 5:4"/>

<verse sid="LAM 5:5"/>We were pursued upon our neck<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">5:5</char><char closed="false" style="ft">'upon our neck':  I.e. 'closely'</char></note>; we grew weary; we were given no rest.<verse eid="LAM 5:5"/>

<verse sid="LAM 5:6"/>Egypt gave a hand<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">5:6</char><char closed="false" style="ft">'gave a hand':  I.e. 'made a pact'</char></note>, Assour, for repletion of bread.<verse eid="LAM 5:6"/>

<verse sid="LAM 5:7"/>Our fathers sinned; they are no more, and we were subject to their lawless deeds.<verse eid="LAM 5:7"/>

<verse sid="LAM 5:8"/>Slaves became our masters; there is no one to redeem from their hand.<verse eid="LAM 5:8"/>

<verse sid="LAM 5:9"/>We shall bring in our bread by our lives, away from before the sword of the wilderness.<verse eid="LAM 5:9"/>

<verse sid="LAM 5:10"/>Our skin became dark like an oven from before the squalls of hunger.<verse eid="LAM 5:10"/>

<verse sid="LAM 5:11"/>They humbled women in Sion, virgins in the cities of Iouda.<verse eid="LAM 5:11"/>

<verse sid="LAM 5:12"/>Rulers were hung up by their hands; elders were not held in honor.<verse eid="LAM 5:12"/>

<verse sid="LAM 5:13"/>Choice men took up the millstone, and young men became weak with wood.<verse eid="LAM 5:13"/>

<verse sid="LAM 5:14"/>Old men ceased from the city gate, choice men from their tunes<note caller="▼" style="f"><char closed="false" style="fr">5:14</char><char closed="false" style="ft">Possibly 'psalms'</char></note>.<verse eid="LAM 5:14"/>

<verse sid="LAM 5:15"/>The joy of our hearts ceased; our dance was turned to mourning.<verse eid="LAM 5:15"/>

<verse sid="LAM 5:16"/>The crown on our head fell; woe indeed to us, for we have sinned.<verse eid="LAM 5:16"/>

<verse sid="LAM 5:17"/>Because of this our heart became grief stricken; because of these things our eyes grew dark,<verse eid="LAM 5:17"/>

<verse sid="LAM 5:18"/>for Mount Sion, because it was obliterated. Foxes passed through it.<verse eid="LAM 5:18"/>

<verse sid="LAM 5:19"/>But you, O Lord, will dwell forever; your throne is for generation and generation.<verse eid="LAM 5:19"/>

<verse sid="LAM 5:20"/>Why will you regarding to victory forget us? Why will you forsake us throughout length of days?<verse eid="LAM 5:20"/>

<verse sid="LAM 5:21"/>Turn us back, O Lord, to you, and we shall turn back, and renew our days as before.<verse eid="LAM 5:21"/>

<verse sid="LAM 5:22"/>For rejecting you have rejected us; you have become exceedingly angry with us.<verse eid="LAM 5:22"/>
</_X_chapter></_X_book></_X_usx>